# CleanMateX Flutter Core Rules

## Mission
Build production-grade Flutter mobile apps for CleanMateX using explicit, maintainable, scalable code. Optimize for solo-developer speed, long-term maintainability, bilingual UX, operational reliability, and zero hidden code.

## Stack
- Flutter stable
- Dart null safety
- Riverpod for state management and dependency injection
- go_router for navigation
- Dio or a centralized HTTP client
- Manual model mapping and serialization only
- flutter_secure_storage for sensitive auth/session data when needed
- Firebase Cloud Messaging for push notifications

## Architecture
Use feature-first structure:

lib/
  core/
    constants/
    errors/
    helpers/
    localization/
    routing/
    services/
    theme/
    utils/
    widgets/
  features/
    <feature_name>/
      data/
        datasources/
        models/
        repositories/
      domain/
        entities/
        repositories/
        usecases/
      application/
        controllers/
        providers/
        states/
      presentation/
        screens/
        widgets/
        dialogs/
        sheets/

## Hard Rules
- Never put API calls directly in widgets.
- Never put business logic inside build().
- Never hardcode user-facing strings.
- Never mix unrelated responsibilities in one file.
- Never use giant god widgets/screens.
- Prefer explicit code over clever abstractions.
- Reuse existing shared widgets and theme utilities before creating new ones.
- Preserve architecture consistency when editing existing code.
- Do not use hidden code generation tools of any kind.
- All important code paths must be visible in source files.

## State Management
- Use Riverpod for async state, dependency injection, and feature controllers.
- Use AsyncValue or equivalent structured async states.
- Use setState only for tiny local UI state.
- Complex screens must have dedicated provider/controller/state handling.
- Keep widget trees passive; state should come from providers/controllers.

## Data Boundaries
- Parse API JSON at the repository/data layer.
- Do not pass raw Map<String, dynamic> through the app unless absolutely required.
- Use typed models.
- Separate DTOs from domain entities when complexity justifies it.
- UI must not know backend JSON structure details.

## Environment and Config
- No API base URL hardcoded in widgets.
- Centralize config, endpoints, timeout policies, headers, and auth attachment.
- All environment-dependent behavior must be isolated.

## Security
- Never hardcode secrets, tokens, private keys, or credentials.
- Never log tokens, passwords, OTPs, or sensitive PII.
- Respect backend authorization. UI hiding is not security.
- Handle unauthorized and expired sessions cleanly.

## Multi-Tenant Awareness
- Always assume tenant context matters.
- Do not hardcode tenant-specific assumptions.
- Feature visibility may depend on plan flags or role.
- Disabled features must fail safely and gracefully.

## Cursor Behavior
Before generating code, infer:
- feature purpose
- user role
- source of truth for state
- API/repository dependencies
- localization impact
- navigation impact
- loading/error/empty states
- offline behavior needs
- tenant/feature-flag implications

When editing code:
- keep naming consistent
- preserve imports structure
- update localization keys if UI text changes
- update routes/providers/repositories if feature wiring changes
- do not silently introduce fake placeholder code
- do not introduce code generation
- do not introduce unnecessary abstraction layers